{{Infobox book | name = Ecological Genetics | image = Ecological Genetics (E B Ford book).jpg | image_size = 200px | caption = | author = [[E. B. Ford]] | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | subject = [[Ecological genetics]] | genre = [[Non-fiction]] | publisher = Chapman & Hall | pub_date = 1964 | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = | isbn = 0412103206| ISBN_note = (3rd edition) | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Ecological Genetics''''' is a 1964 book by the British biologist [[E. B. Ford]] on [[ecological genetics]]. Ford founded the field and it is considered his ''[[Masterpiece|magnum opus]]''. The fourth and final [[edition (book)|edition]] was published in 1975.
Ford's work was celebrated in 1971 by ''Ecological Genetics and Evolution'', a series of essays edited by Robert Creed, publ. Blackwell, Oxford. This included contributions from [[Cyril Darlington]], [[Miriam Rothschild]], [[Theodosius Dobzhansky]], [[Bryan Clarke]], [[A.J. Cain]], Sir [[Cyril Clarke]] and others.
Ford and [[Ronald Fisher]] represented one side of a dispute with the American [[Sewall Wright]] over the relative roles of [[natural selection|selection]] and [[Genetic drift|drift]] in [[evolution]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Evolutionary Genetics|url=http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/evolutionary-genetics/|work=Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy|date=January 14, 2005}}</ref>
